      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Mould and Water Damage Disclosure When Selling Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Brisbane's subtropical climate creates conditions where water ingress and mould are more common than sellers sometimes acknowledge. Here is what the disclosure obligation actually covers, and why transparency protects you.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Mould and water damage sit in a category that makes some Brisbane sellers uncomfortable: they are material facts that must be disclosed, regardless of whether you have tried to fix the problem, regardless of how long ago it happened, and regardless of whether it looks cosmetically acceptable right now. If you knew about it, you disclose it. That is the legal standard in Queensland, and sellers who treat it as optional tend to find out the hard way after settlement.</p>

      <p>Brisbane's climate makes this a more pressing issue here than in most other Australian cities. The combination of high summer humidity, subtropical rainfall events, and the age of the housing stock in the inner east means that water intrusion is not unusual. Roof leaks, failed flashing, rising damp under older Queenslanders, inadequate subfloor ventilation, leaking pipes running through wall cavities, and poor drainage around the foundation are all common sources of water ingress in homes built between the 1920s and 1980s. Each of these creates conditions where mould can establish within days of a moisture event, and once mould is in wall cavities or subfloor framing, it can be difficult to fully remediate without opening the structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the disclosure obligation actually covers</h2>
      <p>Queensland's property disclosure framework requires sellers to disclose defects and material facts they are aware of that would be likely to affect a buyer's decision to buy or the price they would pay. Mould caused by structural water ingress falls squarely within that definition. It affects the structural integrity of the property, the health and liveability of the home, and the cost a buyer will face to remediate it.</p>

      <p>Two categories of water damage are disclosable, not one. The first is current or ongoing water ingress: an active leak, a drainage problem that recurs after rain, damp that appears seasonally. The second is past water damage that has since been addressed: a roof leak that was repaired two years ago, rising damp that was treated and sealed, a section of flooring that was replaced after a pipe burst. Both categories require disclosure if you are aware of them.</p>

      <p>The common misunderstanding is that remediated damage does not need to be disclosed. This is incorrect. A buyer has a legitimate interest in knowing that the property had a significant water event, even if you believe it has been fully fixed. They may want a building inspector to verify the remediation. They may factor it into their assessment of the property's risk profile. That is their right. Your obligation is to tell them what you know.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why painting over mould does not help you</h2>
      <p>Some sellers have addressed visible mould with fresh paint before listing. This is understandable from a presentation standpoint, but it does not affect the disclosure obligation, and it does not reliably conceal the problem from a competent building inspector. An inspector using a moisture meter or thermal imaging camera can identify moisture behind walls and under floors that is invisible to the eye. Mould that has been painted over will typically return if the underlying moisture source has not been fixed.</p>

      <p>More importantly, if a buyer's inspector finds evidence of mould or water damage that was present and known before the sale, and it was not disclosed, the seller is in a significantly worse position than if they had disclosed it upfront. The presence of fresh paint over a mould-affected area tends to reinforce the inference that the seller was aware of the problem. That is not a conversation you want to be having with a buyer's solicitor after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How building inspectors find what you think is hidden</h2>
      <p>A professional building inspection in Brisbane uses several tools that go beyond visual assessment. Moisture meters measure the moisture content of wall linings, floors, and framing. Thermal imaging cameras identify temperature differentials that indicate moisture behind surfaces. Subfloor inspections check the condition of bearers, joists, and piers that are often the first structures to show water damage in older timber homes. Roof cavity inspections assess the condition of sarking, insulation, and framing above the ceiling line.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, where a significant proportion of homes are over forty years old and were built with construction methods that are not particularly water-tight by modern standards, building inspectors find evidence of past or current water damage in the majority of older properties they inspect. A report that notes past water damage alongside a disclosure statement that acknowledges it is a straightforward situation that most buyers can navigate. A report that finds water damage in a property where no disclosure was made is a much more difficult situation to manage, and it can derail a sale or expose you to post-settlement claims.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if you know there is a water issue</h2>
      <p>If you are aware of a water ingress or mould problem, the practical path forward involves three steps: get a proper scope of works from a licensed builder or remediation specialist, carry out the remediation to a standard that can be documented, and disclose what happened and what was done. This approach gives you the most control over the narrative and the price outcome.</p>

      <p>A properly remediated and disclosed issue is a different proposition for a buyer than an undisclosed one that their inspector uncovers mid-campaign. When you disclose and remediate, the buyer has context. They can see the scope of works, the invoices, and the outcome. They may still factor a small discount into their offer, but it is a negotiated and visible adjustment rather than a source of uncertainty and lost confidence. Properties where the seller has been transparent about a known issue and has addressed it properly tend to sell more cleanly than those where the buyer's inspector finds something the seller did not mention.</p>

      <p>If remediation is not feasible before listing, the appropriate path is to disclose the issue, obtain quotes for the remediation work, and price the property to reflect the cost and inconvenience a buyer will face. Under-pricing a disclosed problem is almost always better than the legal and financial exposure of non-disclosure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal risk of non-disclosure</h2>
      <p>Buyers who discover post-settlement mould or water damage that was present and known before the sale have recourse under Queensland property law. The nature and extent of that recourse depends on the specific circumstances, but it can include claims for the cost of remediation, damages, and in serious cases, claims to rescind the contract or seek compensation under consumer protection legislation. These claims are not theoretical: they are a regular feature of property disputes in Queensland, and the legal costs involved in defending or prosecuting them are significant on both sides.</p>

      <p>Transparency is not just the ethical obligation here; it is the financially rational one. The cost of proper remediation before listing, or of disclosing and pricing accordingly, is almost always lower than the cost of defending a post-settlement non-disclosure claim. The uncertainty, time, and stress involved in a legal dispute after settlement should not be underestimated either.</p>

